00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.274
[GUITAR PLAYING]

00:00:05.274 --> 00:00:07.190
DAVE: Today we're joined
by singer-songwriter,

00:00:07.190 --> 00:00:10.660
multi-instrumentalist, recording
artist, and Grammy winner Rob

00:00:10.660 --> 00:00:11.690
Hotchkiss.

00:00:11.690 --> 00:00:14.130
Rob's probably best known
for founding the band Train,

00:00:14.130 --> 00:00:18.740
who released hits including
"Meet Virginia" and "I Am,"

00:00:18.740 --> 00:00:21.320
and their best-known
"Drops of Jupiter,"

00:00:21.320 --> 00:00:23.940
which won the Grammy for
Best Rock Song in 2001.

00:00:23.940 --> 00:00:27.140
Since 2003, Rob's been
pursuing his solo endeavors

00:00:27.140 --> 00:00:30.770
and focusing on songwriting
and raising his family.

00:00:30.770 --> 00:00:32.544
And he's recently
returned to the Bay Area

00:00:32.544 --> 00:00:33.710
and returned to songwriting.

00:00:33.710 --> 00:00:35.668
So today we have a special
performance from him

00:00:35.668 --> 00:00:38.280
and his wife Pamela to show
off some of their new songs.

00:00:38.280 --> 00:00:42.554
So without any further ado,
please welcome Rob Hotchkiss.

00:00:42.554 --> 00:00:47.935
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:47.935 --> 00:00:49.560
ROB HOTCHKISS: Good
evening, Cleveland.

00:00:53.279 --> 00:00:54.820
PAM HOTCHKISS: I
forgot the set list.

00:00:54.820 --> 00:00:56.486
ROB HOTCHKISS: So
here we are at Google.

00:00:56.486 --> 00:00:58.700
You guys are like
innovators, right?

00:00:58.700 --> 00:01:00.280
We're going to do
an experiment here.

00:01:00.280 --> 00:01:02.460
Guitar has a way
to traditionally

00:01:02.460 --> 00:01:08.900
be tuned, E, A, D, G, B,
E. You won't hear that.

00:01:08.900 --> 00:01:12.196
Every guitar I've got
here is tuned differently.

00:01:12.196 --> 00:01:13.320
I have my reasons for that.

00:01:13.320 --> 00:01:16.590
Partly I got bored
after a while.

00:01:16.590 --> 00:01:18.630
Back in Train, actually
in the beginning,

00:01:18.630 --> 00:01:22.850
I would just--you'd write a
song and it just needed to be

00:01:22.850 --> 00:01:23.650
a certain way.

00:01:23.650 --> 00:01:25.340
And I owned one guitar.

00:01:25.340 --> 00:01:27.390
So if you're going
to play shows,

00:01:27.390 --> 00:01:29.390
my thought was, well, I
need to write three more

00:01:29.390 --> 00:01:32.060
songs in that tuning
so I'm not sitting

00:01:32.060 --> 00:01:34.330
there tuning up in front
of people the whole time.

00:01:34.330 --> 00:01:41.351
So this is Dadgad, D-A-D-G-A-D.
Just something I felt like I

00:01:41.351 --> 00:01:43.600
discovered, but some other
people have tried this one.

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:46.490
But a song from
a record we have.

00:01:46.490 --> 00:01:48.810
If you guys want to
grab one when you leave,

00:01:48.810 --> 00:01:51.250
called "Midnight Ghost"
that I made a while ago,

00:01:51.250 --> 00:01:53.080
a song called "Rainmaker."

00:01:53.080 --> 00:01:54.738
Two, three, four.

00:01:54.738 --> 00:01:56.279
[MUSIC - ROB HOTCHKISS,
 "RAINMAKER"]

00:05:10.880 --> 00:05:17.239
[APPLAUSE]

00:05:17.239 --> 00:05:18.280
PAM HOTCHKISS: Thank you.

00:05:18.280 --> 00:05:19.880
ROB HOTCHKISS: And here's one
of those early Train songs.

00:05:19.880 --> 00:05:21.690
This is probably
like-- I think I

00:05:21.690 --> 00:05:26.000
wrote "Free," then "Homesick,"
then probably this one,

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:27.508
called "Eggplant."

00:05:27.508 --> 00:05:29.007
[MUSIC - ROB HOTCHKISS,
 "EGGPLANT"]

00:08:23.171 --> 00:08:27.604
[APPLAUSE]

00:08:27.604 --> 00:08:30.559
ROB HOTCHKISS: And here's my
interpretation of the open G.

00:08:30.559 --> 00:11:58.244
[MUSIC - ROB HOTCHKISS]

00:11:58.244 --> 00:12:01.250
[APPLAUSE]

00:12:01.250 --> 00:16:41.120
[MUSIC - ROB HOTCHKISS]

00:16:41.120 --> 00:16:46.510
[APPLAUSE]

00:16:48.625 --> 00:16:50.750
ROB HOTCHKISS: So Jimmy
Page found that tuning too.

00:16:54.120 --> 00:16:57.250
Now this one I swear I made up.

00:16:57.250 --> 00:17:01.180
So I'm writing a
song, and it just--

00:17:01.180 --> 00:17:04.020
string by string I could
tell what I needed to do

00:17:04.020 --> 00:17:05.349
to get the sound that I wanted.

00:17:05.349 --> 00:17:07.040
And this one's
particularly strange.

00:17:07.040 --> 00:17:10.790
This is a 12-string guitar,
so there's more strings to it.

00:17:10.790 --> 00:17:13.219
But you know, normally
you'd tune it in Ds and As

00:17:13.219 --> 00:17:13.760
or something.

00:17:13.760 --> 00:17:16.119
That makes some sense because
then some of the strings

00:17:16.119 --> 00:17:16.869
would be the same.

00:17:16.869 --> 00:17:20.060
This one needed to be
D sharp and A sharp.

00:17:20.060 --> 00:17:20.764
It just did.

00:17:24.589 --> 00:17:25.837
Song called "Blind Faith."

00:17:25.837 --> 00:17:26.958
Two, three, four.

00:17:26.958 --> 00:17:28.583
[MUSIC - ROB HOTCHKISS, "BLIND
 FAITH"]

